# GameNative — Component Version Fetcher & Updater

## Overview

Every compatibility component (Proton, DXVK, VKD3D, Box64, Turnip, Audio)
is fetched from its official GitHub releases API. The app checks for new
versions on launch and in the Component settings screen. Users can download,
switch between, and remove any version.

This file extends gamenative-game-settings-screen.mdc — read that file
first for the Component screen UI structure.

---

## Implementation checklist (must not be missed)

When implementing or refactoring the Component screen and repository:

1. **GitHub API rate limiting** — Stagger all GitHub API requests by **100ms** apart (e.g. when fetching releases for Proton, DXVK, VKD3D, Box64, Turnip, Mesa). Never fire multiple requests in a tight loop.

2. **Never block UI on network** — Show **cached data immediately** (Room/disk), then **refresh in background**. The UI must never wait on a network call before rendering; if cache is empty, show shimmer placeholders and populate when the first fetch completes.

3. **Download and extract paths** — Download to **context.cacheDir** first (e.g. `File(context.cacheDir, "downloads")`), then **extract to context.filesDir**. Never use external storage (getExternalFilesDir, SD card, etc.) for component installs.

4. **Hardware cache invalidation** — After any **Turnip** or **Mesa** component install completes successfully, call **HardwareProfileCache.invalidate(context)**. The hardware profile (GPU driver path, Vulkan version, etc.) can change; the cache must be invalidated so the next launch or config load sees the new driver.

5. **ACTIVE badge is per-game** — The ACTIVE badge on a component version must reflect the **per-game active version** (the version selected for the current game / appId), not a global “one active version for the whole app”. Two different games can use different Proton (or DXVK, etc.) versions simultaneously. All “set active” and “get active version” APIs must take **appId** (or equivalent) and the UI must be scoped to the game being configured when shown in a game-specific context.

